@node "Device" "Device"
@{b}@{u}Specifing Device@{ub}@{uu}

This is where you can specify what disk you want to look at, but there are
many different ways in telling Inf which disk to look at. You can use a
device name like DF0: or RAM:, a volume name like Data: or "Ram Disk:"
(don't forget to put speech marks around any name with spaces), a directory
(this is just an extention to leaving the device name blank), a file,
 Inf c:Inf, would give you the free space on the disk which held the c:
directory, or an assign, Inf t: would give the free space on which ever
disk the t: directory is assigned to (usually RAM:)

It is also possible to specify several device names, by listing them on the
command line.


@{b}Examples@{ub}

 @{b}4.Data:>@{ub} inf
 @{b}Inf@{ub} v2.2 (28.09.94) by @{i}Michael Askin@{ui}
 "Data:" {61M} = 2,966K (96% full,4% free)
 @{b}4.Data:>@{ub}

 @{b}4.Data:>@{ub} inf "Ram Disk:"
 @{b}Inf@{ub} v2.2 (28.09.94) by @{i}Michael Askin@{ui}
 "Ram Disk:" {216K} = 0 bytes (100% full,0% free)
 @{b}4.Data:>@{ub}

 @{b}4.Data:>@{ub} inf mus:
 @{b}Inf@{ub} v2.2 (28.09.94) by @{i}Michael Askin@{ui}
 "Programs:" {80M} = 1,268K (99% full,1% free)
 @{b}4.Data:>@{ub}

 @{b}4.Data:>@{ub} inf c:inf
 @{b}Inf@{ub} v2.2 (28.09.94) by @{i}Michael Askin@{ui}
 "Boot:" {20M} = 9M (54% full,46% free)
 @{b}4.Data:>@{ub}

and for multiple devices:

 @{b}4.Data:MykFiles/EProgs/inf25>@{ub} inf Boot: Programs: Data: ram:
 @{b}Inf@{ub} 2.5 (20.03.95) ©1995 Michael Askin
 "Boot:" {20M} = 458K (98% full,2% free) Status:OK
 "Programs:" {80M} = 3,307K (96% full,4% free) Status:OK
 "Data:" {61M} = 4,622K (93% full,7% free) Status:OK
 "Ram Disk:" {399K} = 0 bytes (100% full,0% free) Status:OK
@endnode

@node "Output Formats" "Output Formats"
@{b}@{u}Output formats@{ub}@{uu}

There are 3 different output formats.

   - Inf Default. This is the format I decided to use.

   - WB Format. This is the same format as the Usage info on the top of
     WorkBench windows

   - Quiet format. This is the format when the Quiet switch is selected.

@{b}Default format@{ub}

 "Data:" {61M} = 2,995K (96% full,4% free)

   ^       ^       ^      ^       ^
   |       |       |      |     Percentage free
   |       |       |    Percentage used
   |       |     Space left
   |    Total size
  Volume name

@{b}Workbench format@{ub}

 Data: 96% full, 2,995K free, 58M in use

  ^    ^           ^           ^
  |    |           |         Space used
  |    |        Space left
  |   Percentage used
 Volume name

@{b}Quiet format@{ub}

 3067392

    ^
  Amount Left in bytes


@{b}@{u}Examples@{ub}@{uu}

@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub} inf ; Default format
 Inf v2.5 (28.09.94) by Michael Askin
 "Data:" {61M} = 2,995K (96% full,4% free)
@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub}

@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub} inf wb ; Workbench format
 Inf v2.5 (28.09.94) by Michael Askin
 Data: 96% full, 2,995K free, 58M in use
@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub}
 
@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub} inf quiet ; Quiet format
 3067392
@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub}
@endnode

@node "Output Units" "Output Units"
@{b}@{u}Output units@{ub}@{uu}

Normally Inf chooses the most sensible @{"units" link "Units" 0} to use. Sometimes it might be
needed that the output is in a different unit. You can select between @{"bytes" link "Units" 10}
or @{"kilobytes" link "Units" 16}. Use the BYTES switch to select the output to Bytes, use the
KILO switch to select the output to Kilobytes.

@{b}Examples@{ub}

@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub} inf bytes
 Inf v2.5 (28.09.94) by Michael Askin
 "Data:" {64,541,696 bytes} = 3,067,392 bytes (96% full,4% free)
@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub}
 
@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub} inf kilo
 Inf v2.5 (28.09.94) by Michael Askin
 "Data:" {63,029K} = 2,995K (96% full,4% free)
@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub}

You can also use the abbreviations

@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub} inf b
 Inf v2.5 (28.09.94) by Michael Askin
 "Data:" {64,541,696 bytes} = 3,067,392 bytes (96% full,4% free)
@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub}

@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub} inf kb
 Inf v2.5 (28.09.94) by Michael Askin
 "Data:" {63,029K} = 2,995K (96% full,4% free)
@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub}
@endnode

@node "Units" "Units"
@{b}Bits@{ub}

   The smallest possible unit, it has two states, true or false (1 or 0).
   Short for Binary Digit.

@{b}Nibbles@{ub}

   A Nibble is 4 @{"bits" link "Units" 0}, and has 16 different states.. 0 to 15.


@{b}Bytes@{ub}

   A Byte is 8 @{"bits" link "Units" 0}, and has 256 different states.. 0 to 255. This is the
most popular unit for specifying the amount of information.


@{b}Kilobytes@{ub}

   1024 @{"bytes" link "Units" 11}. Remember that it isn't exactly 1000 bytes, 165 Kb is not
165,000 bytes but 168,960 bytes which can sometimes cause confusion.


@{b}Megabytes@{ub}

   1024 @{"kilobytes" link "Units" 17} or 1048576 bytes.


@{b}Blocks@{ub}

   A Block is usually 512 @{"bytes" link "Units" 11}, though on some devices, for example the
   ram disk the block size is 1024 @{"bytes" link "Units" 11}.


Inf chooses between @{"Bytes" link "Units" 10}, @{"Kilobytes" link "Units" 17}, and @{"Megabytes" link "Units" 20}.
@endnode

@node "Watch" "Watch"
@{b}@{u}Watch function@{ub}@{uu}

I don't know why, but this is the option I'm having the most trouble
describing. All it does is continuously shows the info text over and over
again, in the same position, updating it when ever it changes. Try it,
you'll see what I mean.... @{"Inf watch" system "Inf watch >con:0/100/0//PressCtrl-CToQuit"}. Press Ctrl-C to stop.
 @{i}If you can not see the window, try looking at the workbench screen@{ui}


There that was easy!
@endnode

@node "Window" "Window"
@{b}@{u}Window@{ub}@{uu}

The Window switch will make Inf open a window on the default public screen,
and shows the info in the window. This is the same as @{"Watch" link "Watch" 0}, but it shows
the output in a window. The window is fully font sensitive. It is also
possible to open the window on another public screen by using the
@{"PUBLICSCREEN" link "PublicScreen" 0} keyword.

If multiple devices are specified, eg. Inf sys: t: rad: win then only the
first device in the list will be shown, in this case "sys:".

If you have AmigaDos 3.0+, and the picture file in the right place,

@{"Click here for a picture" link "InfWin.ilbm/main" 0}

@{"Click here for a real life example!" system "Inf win >nil:"}
 @{i}Close the window before continuing. If you can't see it, try the workbench
screen.@{ui}
@endnode

@node "PublicScreen" "PUBLICSCREEN"
@{b}@{u}Public Screen@{ub}@{uu}

The public screen @{"keyword" link "ArgLists" 28} can be used to place the window opened from using
the @{"WINDOW" link "Window" 0} switch. You have to specify the public screen that the window is
to be opened on, remember that this name is case sensitive.

For example to open the window on the Directory Opus screen:

 @{b}4.Data:>@{ub} Inf win ps=DOPUS.1

If you don't specify the @{"WINDOW" link "Window" 0} option, then the PUBLICSCREEN option is
ignored.

If the public screen does not exist then an @{"error message" link "errormessages" 0} will be produced.
@endnode

@node "Quiet" "Quiet"
@{b}@{u}Quiet@{ub}@{uu}

Suppress all output text, execept the amount free, which is displayed in
@{"bytes" link "Units" 10}.

eg.

   @{b}4.Data:>@{ub} inf quiet
   3037184
   @{b}4.Data:>@{ub}

@{"Click Here for a Demo" system "Inf quiet >con:0/100///InfDemo/WAIT/Close"} (Click on the Close Gadget to Close the window)
 @{i}If you don't see a window, try looking at the workbench screen@{ui}
@endnode

@node "Installing" "Installing"
@{b}@{u}Installing@{ub}@{uu}

This program does not really need installing. It can be run from anywhere,
and it does not need any libraries. However I suggest that you place the
program somewhere in the path (e.g. The C: directory), and that you put the
manual in a safe place. I usually place all program manuals, docs etc.. in
one directory (called man:). Then using a program called 'man' you can
quickly bring up this guide. Man can be found on @{"Aminet" link "Aminet" 0} as
util/cli/man111a.lha

There is an included installer script to install the program. The default
settings copy Inf to the C: directory, and the man (and related files) to
the man: directory. If you want to install it yourself, or you don't have
the Installer program (which can be found on @{"Aminet" link "Aminet" 0} as
util/misc/Installer-1.25.lzh) then follow these simple steps, replacing the
destination as you please. The optional files are not really nessasary, but
if you have lots of space then shove them on anyway. If you want the icons
aswell, then copy them too.

From the directory which has Inf in it.

 Copy Inf c:             ; Executable
 Copy Inf.guide man:     ; This @{"Guide" link "Inf.guide/main" 0}
 Copy InfWin.ilbm man:   ; A @{"Picture" link "InfWin.ilbm/main" 0} used by this guide (optional)
 Copy Inf.e man:         ; The @{"Source Code" link "Inf.e/main" 0} (optional)
@endnode

@node "ArgLists" "Understanding program argument lists"
To get help from the program put a question mark as an argument, for
example:

@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub} Inf ?
 DEVICE,WB/S,B=BYTES/S,KB=KILO/S,W=WATCH/S,WIN=WINDOW/S,PS=PUBLICSCREEN/K,
 QUIET/S:

The resultant text is called a Template, and tells you how to access the
programs features.

@{b}@{u}/S - Switch@{ub}@{uu}

A switch can be turned on, or off. Normally switches are off unless they
are added to the argument. To turn on Workbench output format type WB after
the program name, for example:

@{b} 4.Data:>@{ub} Inf WB ; WB can be in lower or upper case

@{b}@{u}/A - A Required Argument@{ub}@{uu}

This argument is needed to make the program run, for example the
'addbuffers' program needs a device. This can be added on to other argument
types, for example, /N or /K.

@{b}@{u}/N - Number@{ub}@{uu}

A number is expected.

@{b}@{u}/K - Keyword@{ub}@{uu}

A keyword is expected. For example:

Disk/A, Name/K, Unit/K/N

df0: Name=Empty Unit=0

would statify the above. Note that you don't have to put the '=', a space
can be used instead.

@{b}@{u}/M - Multiple@{ub}@{uu}

Multiple arguments can be given. For example,

   @{b}4.Boot:>@{ub} Copy ?
   FROM/M,TO/A,ALL/S,QUIET/S,BUF=BUFFER/K/N..............

Muliple files can be given to copy.
@endnode

